  "final_answer": "## Il Messaggero's Coverage of Mussolini's Fall and the Badoglio Transition (25-27 July 1943)\n\nIl Messaggero's coverage of this pivotal moment reveals a dramatic editorial transformation across just two days, as the July 26 issue is absent from the archive and the July 25 edition went to press before the late-night announcement of Mussolini's dismissal.\n\n**July 25, 1943**: The newspaper appeared with no mention of the regime change. Articles covered routine fascist affairs, the Sicilian campaign, and Allied bombing damage. The issue reflects the normal fascist-era editorial register, with references to fascist institutions and Mussolini appearing in standard contexts. The dramatic events—the Gran Consiglio meeting at Palazzo Venezia on July 24 and the King's subsequent dismissal of Mussolini—occurred too late for this morning edition.\n\n**July 27, 1943**: The transformation is total and immediate. The front page headline \"La composizione del Governo Badoglio\" (1943-07-27_a000) announces \"Un'altra giornata di entusiastiche dimostrazioni di popolo acclamante all'Italia, alle Forze Armate, al Re e al Maresciallo.\" The newspaper published the Gran Consiglio's order of the day from July 24 (1943-07-27_a006), which had called for restoring \"all state functions\" to the Crown, Gran Consiglio, Government, and Parliament. The resolution, signed by Grandi, Federzoni, and others, passed 19 votes in favor with 7 against.\n\nThe editorial register shifted completely from fascist rhetoric to monarchist-patriotic language. References to \"Risorgimento,\" \"libertà,\" and \"Patria\" replaced fascist terminology. Article 1943-07-27_a040 (\"Carattere del nuovo Governo\") praised the new military government's \"integri funzionari\" chosen for merit rather than \"favore politico,\" and celebrated the return of Carmine Senise as police chief as having \"un chiaro significato\"—emphasizing his reputation as \"un galantuomo specchiato.\"\n\nThe newspaper extensively covered spontaneous popular demonstrations beginning the night of July 25, with crowds singing Risorgimento hymns and the \"Inno di Mameli\" (1943-07-27_a066). Badoglio's appeal to Romans (1943-07-27_a048) warned against assemblies, while the German reaction (1943-07-27_a033) noted the proclamations' emphasis that \"la guerra continui\"—the war would continue.\n\nThis abrupt transition from fascist orthodoxy to monarchist celebration, accomplished without acknowledging the previous regime's existence, demonstrates Il Messaggero's complete editorial realignment within 48 hours.",
